Here's a simple Bun script that starts an HTTP server on `localhost:3000` and responds with "Hello from Bun!" to any request. Bun makes this super easy without needing extra dependencies like Express.

Save this as `server.js`:

```javascript
Bun.serve({
  port: 3000,
  fetch(req) {
    return new Response("Hello from Bun!");
  },
});

console.log("Server running on http://localhost:3000");
```

### How to run it:
1. Make sure you have [Bun installed](https://bun.sh/docs/installation) (e.g., `curl -fsSL https://bun.sh/install | bash`).
2. In your terminal: `bun run server.js`
3. Open http://localhost:3000 in your browser.

Hit `Ctrl+C` to stop the server. Let me know if you want something more complex, like handling routes or reading files! 🚀

input.command:
if ! command -v bun &> /dev/null; then
  echo "Bun is not installed. Please install it first: curl -fsSL https://bun.sh/install | bash"
  exit 1
fi

cat << 'EOF' > /tmp/nova-bun-server.js
Bun.serve({
  port: 3000,
  fetch(req) {
    return new Response("Hello from Bun!");
  },
});

console.log("Server running on http://localhost:3000");
EOF

echo "File written to /tmp/nova-bun-server.js"

cd /tmp
bun run nova-bun-server.js &
SERVER_PID=$!

sleep 3  # Give time for server to start

RESPONSE=$(curl -s -m 5 http://localhost:3000 || echo "Failed to connect")
echo "Server response: $RESPONSE"

kill $SERVER_PID 2>/dev/null || true
rm -f nova-bun-server.js

echo "Server stopped and cleaned up."
